---
description: Catch security anti-patterns in both .NET and React code
alwaysApply: false
globs: ["**/*.cs", "**/*.tsx", "**/*.ts", "**/*.json", "**/*.yml", "**/*.yaml"]
---

## What This Rule Does

Detects security anti-patterns before they reach a commit. Critical findings
block code generation entirely — the agent refuses to produce the violating
code and provides the secure alternative. Warning-level findings are flagged
inline without blocking, but must be acknowledged before proceeding through
`speckit-checklist`.

**Memory references:** `memory-bank/securityStandards.md` (the non-negotiable
vs. warn-level list this rule enforces, including compliance context like
SAMA CSF/PCI DSS), `memory-bank/commonMistakes.md` (previously-caught issues
of this class, e.g. CM-001 disabled webhook verification).

---

## Critical — Refuse to Generate / Flag Immediately

Any of these found in the codebase triggers a hard stop. The agent explains
the risk and provides the secure replacement pattern.

### 1. Hardcoded Secrets in Source Files
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL — .NET: connection string, API key, or password in source
private const string _connStr = "Server=prod.db;Password=P@ssw0rd!;";
// Also in appsettings.json checked into git with real values

// ✅ SECURE — use environment variables or Azure Key Vault references
// appsettings.json: { "ConnectionStrings": { "Default": "" } }
// appsettings.Development.json: (gitignored) real dev string
// Production: injected via Azure Key Vault / environment variable
```

```tsx
// ❌ CRITICAL — React: API key embedded in frontend source
const PAYMENT_SECRET_KEY = "sk_live_abcdef123456"; // exposed in browser bundle

// ✅ SECURE — secret operations go through backend; only publishable keys in frontend
const STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY = import.meta.env.VITE_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY;
```

### 2. JWT Tokens in localStorage
```tsx
// ❌ CRITICAL — XSS attack reads localStorage, exfiltrates token
localStorage.setItem('token', response.accessToken);

// ✅ SECURE — httpOnly cookie (set by server) or in-memory only (React state/Zustand)
// Never stored in localStorage or sessionStorage
// For SPA: keep token in memory, use refresh-token rotation via httpOnly cookie
```

### 3. SQL String Concatenation
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL — SQL injection
var sql = $"SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE UserId = '{userId}'";
var orders = await db.Database.ExecuteSqlRawAsync(sql);

// ✅ SECURE — parameterized via EF Core or explicit parameters
var orders = await db.Orders
    .Where(o => o.UserId == userId)
    .ToListAsync(ct);

// Raw SQL (when genuinely needed) must use parameters:
var orders = await db.Orders.FromSqlRaw(
    "SELECT * FROM Orders WHERE UserId = {0}", userId).ToListAsync(ct);
```

### 4. `[AllowAnonymous]` on Sensitive Endpoints Without Justification
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL — payment endpoint exposed publicly with no auth check
[AllowAnonymous]
[HttpPost("payments/process")]
public async Task<IActionResult> ProcessPayment(PaymentRequest req) { ... }

// ✅ SECURE — remove AllowAnonymous, or add documented justification comment
[Authorize(Policy = "PaymentProcessor")]
[HttpPost("payments/process")]
public async Task<IActionResult> ProcessPayment(PaymentRequest req) { ... }

// Genuinely public endpoints must have a comment:
[AllowAnonymous] // Public: health check, no sensitive data exposed
[HttpGet("health")]
public IActionResult HealthCheck() => Ok();
```

### 5. CORS Policy Allowing `*` Origin in Production
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL — allows any origin to make credentialed requests
app.UseCors(p => p.AllowAnyOrigin().AllowAnyMethod().AllowAnyHeader());

// ✅ SECURE
app.UseCors(p => p
    .WithOrigins(builder.Configuration.GetSection("Cors:AllowedOrigins").Get<string[]>()!)
    .AllowAnyMethod()
    .AllowAnyHeader()
    .AllowCredentials());
```

### 6. `app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage()` Without Environment Guard
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL — stack traces exposed in production
app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage();

// ✅ SECURE
if (app.Environment.IsDevelopment())
    app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage();
else
    app.UseExceptionHandler("/error");
```

### 7. User-Supplied Input Rendered as Raw HTML
```tsx
// ❌ CRITICAL — XSS: attacker-controlled HTML executes in browser
<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: userComment }} />

// ✅ SECURE — sanitize with DOMPurify before rendering, or avoid entirely
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';
<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: DOMPurify.sanitize(userComment) }} />
// Better yet: render as plain text unless rich HTML is a product requirement
<p>{userComment}</p>
```

### 8. `eval()` or `new Function()` in JavaScript/TypeScript
```ts
// ❌ CRITICAL — executes arbitrary code, unacceptable in any context
eval(userInput);
const fn = new Function('x', userInput);

// ✅ SECURE — never use these constructs; if dynamic behavior is needed,
// use a safe pattern (JSON.parse for data, strategy pattern for behavior)
```

### 9. Disabling HTTPS Redirection in Production
```csharp
// ❌ CRITICAL
// Removing app.UseHttpsRedirection() in production config
// or: builder.WebHost.UseUrls("http://0.0.0.0:5000") without TLS termination

// ✅ SECURE
app.UseHttpsRedirection();
app.UseHsts(); // HSTS header for browsers
```

